 use these operators to compare the values of two variables or expressions. For example, if we have two variables \(x\) and \(y\). We will compare the values of \(x\) and \(y\). Comparison always returns either true or false.

| Operator | Operation | Examples |
|----------|-----------|----------|
| ==       | Checks two expressions are equal or not | \(x==y\) |
| !=       | Checks two expressions are not equal or not | \(x!=y\) |
| >        | Checks if left expression is greater than right expression | \(x>y\) |
| <        | Checks if left expression is less than right expression | \(x<y\) |
| >=       | Checks if left expression is greater than or equal to right expression | \(x>=y\) |
| <=       | Checks if left expression is less than or equal to right expression | \(x<=y\) |

#### Relational Operator Example

We use relational operators in Java to compare the values of two expressions. Let us see a program in which we compare two values \(7\) and \(12\) using relational operators.

```java
public class RelationalOperator {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    int a = 7;
    int b = 12;
    System.out.println("Check if a and b are equal: " + (a == b));
    System.out.println("Check if a and b are not equal: " + (a != b));
    System.out.println("Check if a is greater than b: " + (a > b));
    System.out.println("Check if a is less than b: " + (a < b));
    System.out.println("Check if a is greater or equal to b: " + (a >= b));
    System.out.println("Check if a is less or equal to b: " + (a <= b));
  }
}
```

Output:
```
Check if a and b are equal: false
Check if a and b are not equal: true
Check if a is greater than b: false
Check if a is less than b: true
Check if a is greater or equal to b: false
Check if a is less or equal to b: true
```

### Bitwise Operators in Java

As we know that each number in computer memory consists of a combination of binary bits \(0\) and \(1\). Bitwise operations work on bits of both operands. It means that each operand is considered to consist of bits. The operators are applied to the corresponding bits of the operands, that is, each bit in the first operand is applied to the corresponding bit of the second operand. The most common bitwise operators are as follows.

| Syntax | Operation           |
|--------|---------------------|
| \(x | y\) | returns bitwise OR of x and y |
| \(x \& y\) | returns bitwise AND of x and y |
| \(~x\) | returns bitwise complement of x |
| \(x \&\& y\) | returns bitwise XOR of x and y |
| \(x << y\) | left shift of x with y bits |
| \(x >> y\) | right shift of x with y bits |
| \(x >>> y\) | rotate right x with y bits |
| \(x <<\langle y \rangle \) | combine a few bits in a number and "discard" some bits |

Let’s observe some bitwise operators below.

- Bitwise AND
  - Syntax: \(x \& y\)
  - Truth Table: \(\begin{array}{|c|c|c|} \hline x & y & x \& y \\\hline 0 & 0 & 0 \\\hline 0 & 1 & 0 \\\hline 1 & 0 & 0 \\\hline 1 & 1 & 1 \\\hline \end{array}\)

- Bitwise NOT
  - Syntax: \(\sim x\)
  - Truth Table: \(\begin{array}{|c|c|} \hline x & \sim x \\\hline 0 & 1 \\\hline 1 & 0 \\\hline \end{array}\)

- Bitwise OR
  - Syntax: \(x | y\)
  - Truth Table: \(\begin{array}{|c|c|c|} \hline x & y & x | y \\\hline 0 & 0 & 0 \\\hline 0 & 1 & 1 \\\hline 1 & 0 & 1 \\\hline 1 & 1 & 1 \\\hline \end{array}\)

- Bitwise XOR (exclusive OR)
  - Syntax: \(x \&\& y\)
  - Truth Table: \(\begin{array}{|c|c|c|} \hline x & y & x \&\& y \\\hline 0 & 0 & 0 \\\hline 0 & 1 & 1 \\\hline 1 & 0 & 1 \\\hline 1 & 1 & 0 \\\hline \end{array}\)

Below is a table of bitwise operators with operands \(x = 10_2 = 2_{10}\) and \(y = 11_2 = 3_{10}\) of values:

| Operator      | Output | Binary form |
|---------------|--------|-------------|
| \(x \& y\)    | \(2\)  | \(10\)      |
| \(x | y\)     | \(3\)  | \(11\)      |
| \(~x\)        | \(-3\) | \(11\)      |
| \(x \&\& y\)  | \(1\)  | \(01\)      |
| \(x << 1\)    | \(4\)  | \(100\)     |
| \(x >> 1\)    | \(1\)  | \(01\)      |
| \(x >>> 1\)   | \(1\)  | \(01\)      |

#### Bitwise Operator Example

In this example, we demonstrate the usage of various bitwise operators.

```java
public class BitwiseOperator {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
