### Assignment Operators in Java

To save time and effort while writing assignments, we use assignment operators such as “\(\_ \_ = \_ \_ \_ \)” instead of “\(_ \_ = _ \_ \_ \_ + _ \_ \)”. When we use an assignment operator, both values are required, the left is a variable and the right is an expression.

| Syntax    | Assignment                           |
|-----------|--------------------------------------|
| \(b += c\) | \(b = b + c\)                         |
| \(b -= c\) | \(b = b - c\)                         |
| \(b *= c\) | \(b = b * c\)                         |
| \(b /= c\) | \(b = b / c\)                         |
| \(b %= c\) | \(b = b \% c\)                        |
| \(b <<= c\) | \(b = b << c\)                       |
| \(b >>= c\) | \(b = b >> c\)                       |
| \(b >>>= c\) | \(b = b >>> c\)                      |
| \(b &= c\) | \(b = b \& c\)                         |
| \(b ^= c\) | \(b = b \&\& c\)                      |
| \(b |= c\) | \(b = b | c\)                         |

#### Assignment Operator Example

Here, \(a\) is first assigned the value of \(6 + 9\). We used \((=\)) instead of writing \((= 6 + 9)\). Next, the value of \(a\) is assigned to \(b\).

