# All Permutations

According to Problem 46 on Project Euler, the number of permutations of anagrams is \(\frac{d!}{P_1!P_2!P_3!P_4!...P_n!}\), where \(d\) is the total letters and \(P_i\) is the number of repeated letters for each different character in the anagram.

### Solution 1

There is one straightforward way to solve all permutations of a given N character set. For example, `"ABCDE"` will have:

```
5! = 5x4x3x2x1 = 120
```

Each letter combination in the result set will start with `"A_"` 24 times. Then there will be `"B_"`, `"C_"`, `"D_"` and `"E_"` ten times each.

One more thing to note is there is no require that the set of characters are sorted or not. However, a sorted list can help us generate more efficiently.

Based on it, we can answer easily when the character set is sufficiently large, like 26 which is greater than the total number of permutations, it is better to store the result in an array because an efficient permutation generator exists.

Here is one we used in a project.

```java
public class PermutationWalker {
    private int[] set;

    public void init(String str) {
        int len = str.length();
        set = new int[len];
        for (int i = 0; i < len; i++)
            set[i] = str.charAt(i);
        Arrays.sort(set);
    }

    public char get() {
        int i;
        for (i = set.length - 1; i >= 0; i--)
            if (set[i] != -1)
                break;
        return (char) set[i];
    }

    public boolean canGet() {
        return i >= 0;
    }

    private void decrease(int index) {
        if (index == 0)
            return;
        int i = index - 1;

        while (i < index && set[i] == -1)
            i++;
        if (i < index)
            set[i]--;

        for (int j = i + 1; j < index; j++)
            set[j] = set[i] + j - i;

        for (int j = index; j < set.length; j++)
            set[j] = set[j - 1];
    }

    public void decrease() {
        decrease(i);
    }
}
```

Many projects need a solution to generate permutations once at the startup time, then store in a cache and retrieve when needed. This solution is the most efficient cache.

### Solution 2

The best solution offered on GeeksforGeeks.

```java
import java.util.Vector;

public class AllPerms {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str = args.length == 0 ? "geeksforgeeks" : args[0];
        Vector<String> result = permute(str);
        System.out.println(result);
    }

    private static Vector<String> permute(String str) {
        Vector<String> result = new Vector<String>();
        if (str == null || str.isEmpty())
            return result;
        permute("", str, result);
        return result;
    }

    private static void permute(String prefix, String str, Vector<String> result) {
        int N = str.length();
        if (N == 0) {
            result.add(prefix);
        } else {
            for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
                permute(prefix + str.charAt(i), str.substring(0, i) + str.substring(i + 1, N), result);
        }
    }
}
```

### Solution 3

This is the most recursive solution. Just enjoyed it.

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class Permute {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str = args.length == 0 ? "aaa" : args[0];
        List<String> result = new ArrayList<String>();
        permute("", str.toCharArray(), result);
        System.out.println(result);
    }

    private static void permute(String prefix, char[] str, List<String> result) {
        int N = str.length;
        if (N == 0)
            result.add(prefix);
        else {
            for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
                permute(prefix + str[i], erase(str, i), result);
        }
    }

    private static char[] erase(char[] str, int i) {
        char[] ret = new char[str.length - 1];

        System.arraycopy(str, 0, ret, 0, i);
        System.arraycopy(str, i + 1, ret, i, str.length - i - 1);
        return ret;
    }
}
