This shows the use of dynamic casting. Had you used static casting instead of dynamic casting, the code would have blown up because it would have attempted to cast a pointer of type `Node *` to a `MultNode *`, which simply wouldn't have worked. (C++, unlike C, doesn't accept such casting.)

The polymorphic tree shown in Figure 1 is built dynamically, with the help of pointers of type `Node *`. The type of a node to be inserted at a given place is not known until runtime. If you wanted to add a `PowNode`, which would have two children—one a number and the other a numeric expression—you would have to place a pointer of type `Node *` in the tree. If you had used a more general pointer, like `void *`, you'd have to implement the code that would convert a `void *` pointer to a `PowNode *` pointer. As an added benefit, using `void *` would have forced you to cast away the type information and the compiler wouldn't have been able to warn you that you were about to misuse the pointer—in this case, trying to call a virtual method on it.

When runtime polymorphism fails, the type of a variable of an object at runtime can be obtained through the use of `typeid`. The `typeid` operator returns a `type_info` object that contains both a symbol that represents the name of the type in runtime and the member functions that provide printing and comparison services. For example, the `cout` library uses that to print `type_info` objects: “bool” was the symbol string for a boolean object.

When designing a complex system, you must usually model it into a set of subsystems. Each subsystem is essentially a black-box—a global endpoint from which you can get input and get outputs. The subsystems stay separate and don't communicate with one another. Each of them can be imagined as a set of classes that is self-encapsulated, with its own public entry points. Everybody that wishes to communicate with it uses only those entry points, which are exposed as interfaces in the form of public member functions or methods.

If you want to ensure that your public and private parts of the interface remain defined by the same set of functions, you must omit members from the header files and put them in the corresponding translation units. This prevents pull-in libraries that implement the same functionality—you shouldn't live with the same problem twice. In other words, if your new development depends on a library that already exists, you'll have to incorporate it into your project. There's no safe way to prevent pulling in your own libraries. However, there is a way to protect your project from pulling in someone else's library under this same name.

In the above example, the `parse-tree.h` code that I discuss, `Tree.h`, includes no implementation. It's all left for `Tree.c`. There is no connection between the two files. On the one hand, the `parse-tree.h` file assures the developer that it will compile under any platform as long as there is a correct `Tree.c` file. On the other hand, `Tree.h` is guaranteed to remain compilable and fully functioning, because `Tree.h` has none of the declarations that can cause the program to access the implementation part of the header files.

It's more common for library constructors to include an implementation. In this case, however, I am emphasizing the distinction between a class "head" and a class "body".

## Templates and Their Pros and Cons

A template is a generalized syntax. Remember that in many respects a function template is a function that generates or creates functions at runtime. The computer uses the template to generate the final code only when the header files are converted into machine code. That means that the header file that serves as a template with the corresponding implementation are always packaged as a single unit, thus preserving the nondistributable compilation units' mechanism on the programmer's disk. If you review effectively the same code through different mirrors, you'll see that you'll end up with the same result because I made other tweaks to that code that essentially restructure the template properly so that it compiles.

Nevertheless, some code will have problems with certain compilers, even though it has been written in a manner that is generally applicable to any compiler. For example, accessing both a public and a private member of a class in one statement may not work in all compilers. In this case, you may have to split the code into two statements so that one of them is public and the other is private. For example, you might write the following code that constructs an integer in two statements:
