The key point is that squaring a number is equivalent to multiplying itself, and even roots (for example, the square root raised to the power of \(x\)) is equivalent to \(\log_2\). In turn, this implies that multiplying a continuous series of roots is equivalent to adding a continuous series of \(\log_2\).

Since rational numbers are closed under addition, for the product of two sp-fractions, the irrationality measure of their root-polynomial produced corresponds to the sum of the two (product of the two squared) irrationality measures, then multiplying it by \(10^L\), where \(L\) is a sum \(l_{x1} + l_{x2} + ..., +l_{xn}\).

