*The following libraries from the Linux operating system are commonly used in dynamic programming problems:*

**stdio.h:** This header file is used to interact with the standard input/output devices. It contains various input/output functions like printf(), scanf(), getchar(), etc.

**iostream:** This header file is used to interact with the input/output stream. It contains various input/output functions like cin, cout, cerr, etc.

**iomanip:** This header file contains output formatting functions like setw(), setfill(), etc.

**math.h:** This header file contains various mathematical functions like sqrt(), pow(), etc.

**string.h:** This header file contains various string manipulation functions like strcat(), strcpy(), etc.

**cstring:** This header file contains various string manipulation functions like strlen(), strcmp(), etc.

**algorithm:** This header file contains various sorting and searching algorithms like sort(), binary_search(), lower_bound(), etc.

**queue:** This header file contains the queue data structure like push(), pop(), front(), etc.  

The following problem can be solved using some of the above-mentioned libraries of the Linux operating system from the dynamic programming perspective in the C++ language:

**Bomb Disposal**

The problem is as follows: You are given a matrix of bombs, each of which explodes exactly once. When a bomb is exploded, it destroys itself and adjacent bombs. You have to find the number of bombs remaining when all of them explode.

Here is a sample code to solve this problem using the above-mentioned libraries:

```cpp
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n,m;
    cin>>n>>m; // take input of matrix size
    vector<vector<bool>> bomb(n,vector<bool>(m,false)); // create a matrix of bombs
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        for(int j=0;j<m;j++)
            cin>>bomb[i][j]; // take input of the matrix
    queue<pair<int,int>> q; // create a queue for DFS traversal
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        for(int j=0;j<m;j++)
            if(bomb[i][j])
                q.push({i,j}); // push the bombs to the queue
    while(!q.empty()) {
        int i=q.front().first; // take the coordinates of the current bomb
        int j=q.front().second;
        q.pop(); // pop the current bomb from the queue
        bomb[i][j]=false; // set the current bomb to false
        if(i>0 && bomb[i-1][j]) { // if the bomb has a left neighbor
            bomb[i-1][j]=false; // set the left neighbor to false
            q.push({i-1,j}); // push the left neighbor to the queue
        }
        if(i<n-1 && bomb[i+1][j]) { // if the bomb has a right neighbor
            bomb[i+1][j]=false; // set the right neighbor to false
            q.push({i+1,j}); // push the right neighbor to the queue
        }
        if(j>0 && bomb[i][j-1]) { // if the bomb has an upper neighbor
            bomb[i][j-1]=false; // set the upper neighbor to false
            q.push({i,j-1}); // push the upper neighbor to the queue
        }
        if(j<m-1 && bomb[i][j+1]) { // if the bomb has a lower neighbor
            bomb[i][j+1]=false; // set the lower neighbor to false
            q.push({i,j+1}); // push the lower neighbor to the queue
        }
    }
    int ans=0;
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        for(int j=0;j<m;j++)
            ans+=bomb[i][j]; // count the remaining bombs
    cout<<ans<<endl; // print the answer
    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we first take the input of the matrix size and the matrix of bombs. Then we create a queue for DFS traversal and push all the bombs to the queue. Then we use a while loop to pop the current bomb from the queue, set it to false, and check if it has any neighbors which are still not set to false. If it has a left neighbor, then we set the left neighbor to false and push it to the queue, and similarly for the right, upper, and lower neighbors. In the end, we count the remaining bombs and print the answer.

