Your example of using a queue to solve a problem reminiscent of the butter bungee jump challenge is one where you would expect the initial state of objects such as mountains to remain unchanged once the bombs explode.

So, let's reason this out. When a bomb at position (i, j) explodes, it destroys itself and any adjacent objects in the direction its movement vector, which is denoted as \( \mathbf{v} \). Each object is destroyed if its current position is exactly \( \mathbf{v} \) away from the previous position of the object that contains the bomb and the movement vector \( \mathbf{v} \) points towards that object.

In essence, you move the object at (i, j) by \( \mathbf{v} \) and continue this operation until you run out of objects to move or until no more objects are affected. The initial problem was asking how many objects would remain in the system after the bungee jumpers exploded, and your queue implementation is a way to efficiently simulate this process.

Let's consider the initial board setup. There will always be a 1 by 1 'block' somewhere on the board. As such, we can assume that this 'block' is the first one to be plotted, followed by the next, and so on. Thus, every subsequent object will be 'moved' by one position horizontally or vertically, and it will forever remain in that position until a 'push' results in its destruction.

If every object has some kind of internal state that keeps track of its previous position, then we can simply trace its movement until a 'push' occurs. More generically, we can say that if 'push' is performed on an object, then the object will move to its current position, except for the 'block'. Under this constraint, we can use a breadth-first search to travel the entire board, identifying any objects that move in the same direction that the 'bungee jumper' might move.

For example, given a board \( b \) with \( n \) rows and \( m \) columns, we could perform a BFS using a set \( S \) to record the positions of already-visited objects. Then, for every cell \( (i, j) \), we could check if \( b[i][j] = 1 \), in which case we would add it to \( S \) and remove it from \( b \). Then, we would iterate over the cells \( (i + 1, j) \), \( (i - 1, j) \), \( (i, j + 1) \), and \( (i, j - 1) \) and if they are not in \( S \), we would recursively add them to \( S \) and remove them from \( b \).

We can stop at some point and print the number of elements in \( S \) as the number of objects that remain in the system. Using this procedure, we can compute the number of remaining objects for any given board configuration.

